{
  "executive_summary": "Architecture for a real-time ML delivery time estimation service with a decoupled training pipeline and blue-green model serving. The system splits cleanly into three bounded contexts: Feature Engineering (data preparation), Model Training Pipeline (offline weekly retraining), and Prediction Service (online low-latency inference). The 100ms P99 constraint during checkout drives the core architectural decision: pre-computed features, in-process model serving (no network hop to a separate model server), and blue-green model deployment with instant rollback. Designed for a 4-person team — simplicity is paramount.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Prediction Service",
        "responsibility": "Serves real-time delivery time predictions at checkout. Loads the model in-process, assembles features, runs inference, returns predicted minutes. This is the hot path.",
        "boundaries": "Owns the inference runtime, feature assembly, model version management, and health checks. Does NOT own training, feature engineering logic definitions, or data collection."
      },
      {
        "name": "Feature Store",
        "responsibility": "Stores pre-computed and real-time features (courier load snapshots, zone historical averages, weather cache). Provides a unified feature vector for both training and serving to prevent train-serve skew.",
        "boundaries": "Owns feature schemas and versioning. Backed by Redis for online serving (sub-ms lookups) and Parquet/S3 for offline training. Does NOT own raw data or feature computation logic."
      },
      {
        "name": "Feature Pipeline",
        "responsibility": "Computes and materializes features from raw delivery data, weather APIs, and courier telemetry. Runs on a schedule (hourly for real-time features like courier load, daily for historical aggregates).",
        "boundaries": "Owns feature transformation logic and data quality checks. Writes to Feature Store. Does NOT serve predictions or manage models."
      },
      {
        "name": "Training Pipeline",
        "responsibility": "Weekly batch job that pulls features + labels from the Feature Store, trains/validates a new model, runs evaluation against the champion model, and publishes the candidate to the Model Registry.",
        "boundaries": "Owns training logic, hyperparameter tuning, evaluation metrics, and data splitting. Does NOT deploy models to production — that is a separate promotion step."
      },
      {
        "name": "Model Registry",
        "responsibility": "Versioned store of trained model artifacts with metadata (metrics, training data range, feature schema version). Supports tagging models as champion/challenger and maintains rollback history.",
        "boundaries": "Owns model artifact storage and version metadata. Implemented as S3 + a metadata table (PostgreSQL). Does NOT run training or serving."
      },
      {
        "name": "Model Deployer",
        "responsibility": "Promotes a candidate model to production using blue-green deployment. Signals the Prediction Service to load the new model. Monitors post-deployment metrics and triggers automatic rollback if error rate or latency degrades.",
        "boundaries": "Owns deployment orchestration, canary analysis, and rollback triggers. Does NOT own the model artifacts or the serving infrastructure itself."
      },
      {
        "name": "Monitoring & Observability",
        "responsibility": "Tracks prediction latency (P50/P95/P99), model accuracy (predicted vs actual delivery time logged post-delivery), feature drift, and data quality. Alerts on SLA breaches and model degradation.",
        "boundaries": "Owns dashboards, alerts, and the feedback loop that logs actual delivery times back for future training."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "Checkout Service (external)",
        "to": "Prediction Service",
        "contract": "POST /predict { weight, distance, zone, time_of_day } → { predicted_minutes, confidence_interval, model_version } — must respond within 100ms P99",
        "coupling_type": "synchronous REST, tight latency coupling"
      },
      {
        "from": "Prediction Service",
        "to": "Feature Store (Redis)",
        "contract": "GET features by (zone, courier_id, weather_station) → pre-computed feature vector. Sub-millisecond. Fallback to defaults on cache miss.",
        "coupling_type": "synchronous, data coupling"
      },
      {
        "from": "Prediction Service",
        "to": "Model Registry (S3)",
        "contract": "Pull model artifact by version tag (champion). Loaded at startup and on deployment signal — NOT on every request.",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous, loaded at deploy-time only"
      },
      {
        "from": "Feature Pipeline",
        "to": "Feature Store",
        "contract": "Batch write of computed feature vectors. Schema-versioned. Writes to both Redis (online) and S3/Parquet (offline).",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous batch"
      },
      {
        "from": "Training Pipeline",
        "to": "Feature Store (S3/Parquet)",
        "contract": "Read historical feature vectors + delivery time labels for training window.",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous batch read"
      },
      {
        "from": "Training Pipeline",
        "to": "Model Registry",
        "contract": "Publish trained model artifact + evaluation metrics + feature schema version.",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous"
      },
      {
        "from": "Model Deployer",
        "to": "Prediction Service",
        "contract": "Signal to load new model version (lightweight RPC or file-watch on model path). Health check confirms new model is serving.",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous signal, loose coupling"
      },
      {
        "from": "Monitoring",
        "to": "Model Deployer",
        "contract": "Alert on degradation → trigger rollback to previous champion.",
        "coupling_type": "event-driven"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "1) Feature Pipeline runs hourly/daily: ingests raw delivery data, weather API, courier telemetry → computes features → writes to Feature Store (Redis for online, S3 for offline). 2) Weekly Training: Training Pipeline reads labeled data from Feature Store (S3) → trains model → evaluates against champion → publishes candidate to Model Registry. 3) Deployment: Model Deployer promotes candidate → signals Prediction Service → Prediction Service loads new model in-process (blue-green swap). 4) Serving: Checkout calls Prediction Service → service fetches pre-computed features from Redis → runs in-process inference → returns prediction. 5) Feedback: Actual delivery times are logged post-delivery → joined with predictions → fed back into Feature Store for next training cycle.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "In-Process Model Serving",
        "rationale": "100ms P99 is tight. A network hop to a separate model server (e.g., TensorFlow Serving) adds 5-20ms of latency plus failure modes. Loading the model directly in the prediction service process (e.g., ONNX Runtime, LightGBM native) eliminates this. For a gradient-boosted tree on 6-10 features, inference is <1ms."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Blue-Green Model Deployment",
        "rationale": "Business requires instant rollback. Two model slots (blue/green) in the Prediction Service — one active, one standby. New model loads into standby, traffic switches atomically, rollback is just switching back. Zero-downtime, zero-risk."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Offline/Online Feature Store Split",
        "rationale": "Prevents train-serve skew — the #1 silent killer of ML systems. Same feature definitions serve both training (read from S3/Parquet) and inference (read from Redis). Feature Pipeline is the single writer."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Champion/Challenger Model Evaluation",
        "rationale": "New model must beat the current champion on held-out validation data before it can be promoted. Prevents regressions from reaching production. Combined with post-deploy monitoring for defense in depth."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Graceful Degradation with Feature Defaults",
        "rationale": "If Redis is unavailable or a feature is missing, the Prediction Service falls back to zone-level defaults (precomputed averages) rather than failing the checkout. Availability > precision in a checkout flow."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Prediction Serving",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["PredictionRequest (value object: order features → predicted minutes)", "ModelVersion (entity: version ID, status, loaded artifact, metrics)", "FeatureVector (value object: assembled features for a single prediction)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Model Lifecycle",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["TrainedModel (entity: artifact, evaluation metrics, feature schema version, training data range)", "TrainingRun (entity: run ID, hyperparameters, dataset version, results)", "DeploymentEvent (entity: model version, deployment time, rollback flag)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Feature Engineering",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["FeatureDefinition (entity: name, computation logic, version)", "MaterializedFeature (value object: feature name + value + timestamp)", "FeatureSchema (entity: ordered list of features expected by a model version)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Observability",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": ["PredictionLog (value object: prediction + actual delivery time for accuracy tracking)", "LatencyMetric (value object: P50/P95/P99 per time window)", "DriftAlert (event: feature distribution shift detected)"]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Feature Engineering",
        "downstream": "Prediction Serving",
        "relationship": "Conformist — Prediction Service conforms to the feature schema published by Feature Engineering. Feature schema version is pinned to model version to prevent mismatch."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Feature Engineering",
        "downstream": "Model Lifecycle",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — Training Pipeline requests features in a specific format; Feature Engineering supplies them. Schema is versioned."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Model Lifecycle",
        "downstream": "Prediction Serving",
        "relationship": "Open Host Service — Model Registry publishes artifacts in a standard format (ONNX/LightGBM binary). Prediction Service loads any version via a stable interface."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Prediction Serving",
        "downstream": "Observability",
        "relationship": "Published Language — Prediction Service emits structured logs/events that Observability consumes. No coupling back."
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "In-process model serving instead of dedicated model server (TFServing, Triton)",
      "gains": "Eliminates network hop (saves 5-20ms), simpler infrastructure, fewer moving parts for a 4-person team, easier to debug",
      "sacrifices": "Model and service are deployed together, no GPU inference (CPU only), harder to share model across multiple services",
      "alternatives_considered": ["TensorFlow Serving / Triton Inference Server — better for deep learning models or multi-model serving, but adds latency and ops burden", "Sidecar model server — compromise, but still adds a network hop"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "LightGBM / XGBoost over deep learning",
      "gains": "Sub-millisecond CPU inference on tabular data, interpretable feature importances, simple training pipeline, well-suited to 6-10 structured features, small team can maintain it",
      "sacrifices": "Cannot easily incorporate unstructured inputs (text, images) if needed later, may plateau on accuracy vs deep models on very large datasets",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Neural network (MLP/Transformer) — overkill for 6-10 tabular features, needs GPU serving, 4-person team can't maintain this", "Linear regression with feature engineering — simpler but likely worse accuracy for non-linear interactions like weather × time_of_day"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Redis for online feature store instead of pre-loading all features into the service",
      "gains": "Features update independently of service deploys, shared source of truth, scales to many feature dimensions",
      "sacrifices": "Adds ~1ms network call, Redis becomes a dependency on the hot path (mitigated by defaults fallback)",
      "alternatives_considered": ["In-memory feature cache refreshed periodically — eliminates Redis dependency but features may be stale and requires more memory per instance", "Compute features on the fly — eliminates store dependency but risks train-serve skew and adds latency"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Weekly retraining batch job instead of continuous/online learning",
      "gains": "Simple, predictable, easy to validate before deploy, matches team capacity, weekly cadence sufficient for delivery patterns (they don't change hourly)",
      "sacrifices": "Model lags real-world changes by up to a week (e.g., new road closure), cannot adapt to sudden distribution shifts",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Daily retraining — more responsive but higher ops burden and data may not accumulate enough signal daily", "Online learning — most responsive but extremely hard to validate, debug, and roll back; inappropriate for team size"]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Model algorithm",
      "evolution_path": "The ONNX interchange format allows swapping LightGBM → XGBoost → neural net without changing the Prediction Service. The service loads any ONNX model. Team can experiment with algorithms freely."
    },
    {
      "area": "Feature set",
      "evolution_path": "Feature schema is versioned and decoupled from the model. New features (e.g., traffic data, holiday calendar) can be added to the Feature Pipeline and used in next training run without modifying the serving path — just extend the schema version."
    },
    {
      "area": "Retraining cadence",
      "evolution_path": "Training Pipeline is a scheduled job. Changing weekly → daily is a config change. The pipeline, registry, and deployer are cadence-agnostic."
    },
    {
      "area": "Serving infrastructure",
      "evolution_path": "If the team grows or latency requirements tighten, the in-process model can be extracted to a dedicated inference service behind a gRPC interface. The Prediction Service becomes a thin gateway."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "Feature Store as single source of truth",
      "reason": "Train-serve skew is the most dangerous failure mode in ML systems. The constraint that ALL features flow through the Feature Store (no ad-hoc feature computation in the serving path) must be enforced rigidly. Violating this will cause silent accuracy degradation."
    },
    {
      "area": "Model evaluation gate before deployment",
      "reason": "No model reaches production without beating the champion on held-out data. This gate prevents regressions. The business explicitly requires rollback capability — this gate is the first line of defense."
    },
    {
      "area": "100ms P99 latency budget",
      "reason": "This is a checkout-path SLA. The budget breakdown is rigid: ~1ms feature fetch, ~1ms inference, ~3ms serialization/network overhead, ~95ms safety margin. Any component that threatens this budget must be rejected."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "Train-serve skew — features computed differently at training time vs serving time, causing silent accuracy degradation",
      "severity": "critical",
      "mitigation": "Single Feature Store with shared feature definitions for both online (Redis) and offline (S3) paths. Feature schema is versioned and pinned to model version. Integration tests validate feature parity."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Redis failure on the hot path degrades checkout experience",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Feature defaults fallback (zone-level historical averages baked into the service at deploy time). Circuit breaker on Redis calls with <5ms timeout. Prediction still returns — just less precise."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Model degradation goes undetected — new model performs well on validation but poorly on live traffic",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Post-deployment monitoring compares predicted vs actual delivery times (logged after delivery). Auto-rollback if MAE increases >15% over 1-hour window. Shadow mode option for high-risk model changes."
    },
    {
      "risk": "4-person team spread too thin across ML + platform concerns",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Clear ownership split: 2 ML engineers own Feature Pipeline + Training Pipeline + model quality. 2 platform engineers own Prediction Service + Model Deployer + infrastructure. Feature Store is shared — establish clear interface contracts early."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Feedback loop delay — actual delivery times arrive hours after prediction, slowing model iteration",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "This is inherent to the domain and acceptable with weekly retraining. Ensure the delivery completion event pipeline is reliable and delivery times are joined correctly with predictions by request ID."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Weather API latency or unavailability affects feature pipeline",
      "severity": "low",
      "mitigation": "Weather features are pre-computed and cached in Feature Store, not fetched at prediction time. Weather API is called in the Feature Pipeline (offline/batch), not on the hot path. Stale weather (up to 1 hour) is acceptable."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Phase 1 (Weeks 1-3): Prediction Service + simple heuristic model (distance/zone lookup table) serving via REST. Establish the 100ms P99 SLA with monitoring. Set up Redis-backed Feature Store with the 6 core features. Phase 2 (Weeks 4-6): Training Pipeline — LightGBM model trained on historical delivery data, exported as ONNX. Model Registry on S3 with PostgreSQL metadata. Blue-green model loading in Prediction Service. Phase 3 (Weeks 7-8): Model Deployer with champion/challenger evaluation gate and auto-rollback. Feature Pipeline scheduled jobs for real-time features. End-to-end monitoring with prediction-vs-actual accuracy tracking. Technology choices: Python (FastAPI) for Prediction Service with ONNX Runtime for inference, Redis for online features, S3 + Parquet for offline features, LightGBM for initial model, PostgreSQL for model registry metadata, Prometheus + Grafana for monitoring.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "services/prediction-service/ — FastAPI app with ONNX Runtime, blue-green model loader, feature assembler, health checks",
      "services/prediction-service/model_loader.py — Blue-green model management: load, swap, rollback",
      "services/prediction-service/feature_client.py — Redis feature fetch with timeout + defaults fallback",
      "pipelines/feature-pipeline/ — Scheduled feature computation jobs (hourly courier load, daily aggregates, hourly weather)",
      "pipelines/training-pipeline/ — Weekly training job: data pull, train, evaluate, publish to registry",
      "pipelines/training-pipeline/evaluate.py — Champion/challenger comparison on held-out data",
      "infrastructure/model-registry/ — S3 artifact storage + PostgreSQL metadata schema",
      "infrastructure/model-deployer/ — Promotion script: evaluate gate → signal prediction service → monitor → rollback",
      "shared/feature-schema/ — Versioned feature definitions shared between training and serving",
      "monitoring/dashboards/ — Grafana dashboards for latency, accuracy, feature drift",
      "tests/integration/ — Train-serve skew detection tests, latency budget tests, rollback tests"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Use ONNX as the model interchange format to decouple training framework from serving runtime. Feature schema versioning must be enforced — every model artifact must declare which feature schema version it expects. The Prediction Service must validate feature schema compatibility at model load time, not at request time. Use structured logging with request IDs to join predictions with actual delivery outcomes. Keep the Training Pipeline idempotent — re-running with the same data should produce the same result.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "DO NOT compute features at prediction time — all features must be pre-computed and fetched from the Feature Store. Computing on-the-fly causes train-serve skew and latency spikes.",
      "DO NOT call external APIs (weather, traffic) in the prediction hot path — these add 50-500ms latency and will blow the P99 budget.",
      "DO NOT deploy models without the evaluation gate — even 'small' model changes can cause regressions. The champion/challenger pattern is non-negotiable.",
      "DO NOT use a separate model serving infrastructure (TFServing, Seldon) for this use case — it adds operational complexity that a 4-person team cannot sustain, and the latency overhead is unnecessary for a single tabular model.",
      "DO NOT version features independently from models — a model must always be pinned to a specific feature schema version. Mismatch here is the most common source of silent ML failures.",
      "DO NOT skip the defaults fallback in the Prediction Service — Redis will fail eventually, and failing checkout is worse than returning a slightly less accurate prediction."
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 88,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "In-process model serving is the right call for 100ms P99 on tabular data with a 4-person team",
      "Blue-green model deployment with champion/challenger gate satisfies the rollback requirement cleanly",
      "Feature Store split (Redis online / S3 offline) is the standard pattern to prevent train-serve skew",
      "LightGBM/XGBoost is the right model class for 6-10 structured features with low-latency CPU inference"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Exact feature refresh cadence (hourly courier load may need to be more frequent during peak hours — needs empirical tuning)",
      "Auto-rollback threshold (15% MAE increase is a starting point — needs calibration against business tolerance)",
      "Whether the team will need a proper feature store framework (Feast, Tecton) or if custom Redis + S3 is sufficient long-term"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "The model is tabular (gradient-boosted trees) — not deep learning. If the team plans to use neural networks, the serving architecture changes significantly.",
      "Order volume is in the range of hundreds to low thousands of predictions per second — not tens of thousands. At very high scale, the Prediction Service needs horizontal scaling and Redis clustering.",
      "Weather data is available via a reliable third-party API with reasonable latency for batch ingestion.",
      "Historical delivery data with actual delivery times exists and is of reasonable quality for training.",
      "The checkout service can tolerate a gracefully degraded prediction (zone-average fallback) during Feature Store outages."
    ]
  }
}

